I awoke after a few hours sleep at 5am to see the Milky Way low in the sky above Cape Palliser. The only problem was my camera gear was at the top of the lighthouse as seen in the right of this image. I had set up a time-lapse there a few hours before, so I had to climb the 250 plus steps up there to retrieve my gear before I could take this photo. By the time I got back the sky was beginning to get lighter with sunrise 2 hours away. I took a wide pano made up of 20 individual images to get this shot. According to data collected by a coalition of top scientific and medical research groups, the majority are spending more time writing grants for less payoff than just three years ago. Nearly 20 percent report they\u2019re considering more supportive climes overseas...\n\nMore than 3,700 scientists from all 50 states participated in the study, offering online responses in June and July 2013. They offered sobering assessments of the state of their profession. Eighty percent said they were spending more of their time writing grants now than in 2010, while 67 percent said they were receiving less grant money now than they were back then. Only two percent of respondents said they had received money from their employers \u2014 predominantly academic institutions \u2014 to make up for the loss of federal funds.\n\nAccording to the survey, 68 percent of respondents said they do not have the funds to expand their research operations; 55 percent said they have a colleague who has lost a job or expects to soon; and 18 percent of respondents said they were considering continuing their careers in another country.\n\nTo read the rest of this short article by Lindsay Abrams, go here: http://bit.ly/187CeUV\n\nHat tip to Zack Kopplin for pointing me to this.\n\nImage Credit: American Society for Biochemistry and Molecular Biology"}

Over the decades, these satellites have provided invaluable information, and the vantage point of space has provided new perspectives on Earth. This book celebrates Earth\u2019s aesthetic beauty in the patterns, shapes, colors, and textures of the land, oceans, ice, and atmosphere. The book features 75 stunning images of Earth from the Terra, Landsat 5, Landsat 7, EO-1, and Aqua satellites. Sensors on these satellites can measure light outside of the visible range, so the images show more than what is visible to the naked eye. The five-person crew of the STS-7 mission deployed two communications satellites and conducted pharmaceutical experiments. Ride was the first woman to use the robot arm in space and the first to use the arm to retrieve a satellite. Her second space flight was in 1984, also on board the Challenger. That is kind of the opposite of chaos.\n\n\"(Scientists often speak of 'collapse and revival' of wave groups, and this video shows that nicely.)\n\n\"We do have a demo that shows chaotic motion with pendula very nicely. While there are calculators that will solve for any variable in the equation you enter they do not help you understand what is going on behind the curtain. The critical skill learned in algebra is understanding what the whys and wherefores of a problem are and how to approach a solution to a new and interesting type of problem. A steadily increasing share is conducted for, by, or at the direction of, the Federal government.\n\nToday, the solitary inventor, tinkering in his shop, has been overshadowed by task forces of scientists in laboratories and testing fields. In the same fashion, the free university, historically the fountainhead of free ideas and scientific discovery, has experienced a revolution in the conduct of research. Partly because of the huge costs involved, a government contract becomes virtually a substitute for intellectual curiosity. For every old blackboard there are now hundreds of new electronic computers.\n\nThe prospect of domination of the nation's scholars by Federal employment, project allocations, and the power of money is ever present \u2013 and is gravely to be regarded.\n\nYet, in holding scientific research and discovery in respect, as we should, we must also be alert to the equal and opposite danger that public policy could itself become the captive of a scientific-technological elite.\"\n\nFrom Dwight D. By controlling how materials are assembled on the nanoscale level, they hope to create new technologies, from solar cells to faster (heck, maybe even cheaper) electronics.\n\nFor more on Batteas and his group's research, go to http://www.chem.tamu.edu/faculty/batteas.\n\n++++++++\n\n(COOLNESS ALERT: white scale bar in photos = two microns. One micron = one-millionth of a meter.  100 microns = thickness of a human hair.  So you could print about 10 of these pumpkins across a single human hair.
